    <div class="risk-box">
      <h4>Crisis Summary</h4>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Licensed buying companies owe banks:</strong> GHS 7-8 billion ($650-750 million)</li>
        <li><strong>Farmer arrears (Nov-Dec 2025):</strong> $205-234 million — UNPAID as of last reports</li>
        <li><strong>Cocoa price collapse:</strong> $8,000/tonne peak → $3,500-4,100/tonne current</li>
        <li><strong>Banking sector exposure:</strong> Material — systemic risk if buyer defaults cascade</li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <h2>What Happened</h2>

    <p>Ghana's cocoa sector — the country's largest agricultural export and a cornerstone of the rural economy — is in its worst crisis in a generation. The chain of causation:</p>

    <ol>
      <li><strong>Global cocoa price collapse:</strong> After reaching $8,000/tonne in 2024 due to West African supply disruptions, prices crashed to the $3,500-4,100 range</li>
      <li><strong>Cocobod forward-sold at lower prices:</strong> Ghana's Cocoa Board had committed to forward contracts at prices below the peak, locking in revenue that now looks adequate but left no buffer</li>
      <li><strong>Licensed buying companies (LBCs) undercapitalized:</strong> The LBCs that purchase cocoa from farmers and sell to Cocobod accumulated GHS 7-8 billion in bank debt</li>
      <li><strong>Farmer payments delayed:</strong> Farmers who delivered cocoa in November-December 2025 have not been fully paid — $205-234 million in arrears</li>
    </ol>

