    <h2>Government Reform Package</h2>

    <p>The Mahama administration has announced the most comprehensive cocoa reform package in recent memory:</p>

    <ul>
      <li>Immediate farmer payments (status: ANNOUNCED, not confirmed delivered)</li>
      <li>Domestic cocoa bonds as new financing instrument</li>
      <li>Legislation to guarantee 70% of FOB price to farmers</li>
      <li>50% local processing target (currently ~35%)</li>
      <li>COCOBOD refocused on core regulatory mandate</li>
      <li>Reintroduction of free fertiliser for cocoa farmers</li>
      <li>National cocoa traceability system</li>
    </ul>

    <div class="risk-box">
      <h4>GhanaScope Reality Check</h4>
      <p>The reform package reads well on paper. But GhanaWorld applies <strong>Failure Pattern FP-004</strong> (Policy-Announcement Dependency): Ghana has a long history of ambitious agricultural reform announcements that stall in implementation.</p>
      <p>Key questions still unanswered:</p>
      <ul>
        <li>When will the farmer payments actually clear? (As of last confirmed reports: STILL UNPAID)</li>
        <li>How will domestic cocoa bonds be structured and who buys them?</li>
        <li>What enforcement mechanism ensures 70% FOB price guarantee?</li>
        <li>How does COCOBOD service its existing debt while funding reforms?</li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <h2>Investment Implications</h2>

    <h3>For Diaspora Investors Considering Cocoa</h3>

    <p><strong>DO NOT enter cocoa primary production or LBC operations right now.</strong> The financial structure is broken and the reform timeline is uncertain.</p>

    <p><strong>Potential opportunity in 12-18 months:</strong> If the 50% local processing target gains traction, cocoa processing (butter, powder, chocolate) could present an entry point. But only after:</p>

    <ul>
      <li>Farmer payments are confirmed cleared</li>
      <li>LBC debt restructuring is completed</li>
      <li>Processing incentives are legislated (not just announced)</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>For Investors in Other Sectors</h3>

    <p><strong>Monitor banking sector exposure.</strong> If LBC defaults trigger bank provisioning, credit availability across all sectors could tighten. This is the primary contagion risk.</p>

    <p><strong>Watch the cedi.</strong> Reduced cocoa forex earnings could put pressure on the exchange rate in H2 2026, especially if gold prices don't hold current levels ($4,400+/oz).</p>

